<dl id="n56196i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n56" href="#n56196i">N56 (VI.B.41)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n56all.htm#n56196i"> 196(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> puddling <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n56196i"> <li>FW unlocated</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Cast-iron is not pure iron, but contains carbon, which it gets from the coal; we can burn the carbon away (by a process called <mark>puddling</mark>), and we thus can get wrought-iron from castiron. <small> H. E. Roscoe, <a name="HERC3" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#HERC3"><cite title="source">Science Primer: Chemistry</cite></a> (n.d.) 92</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Puddling: a process of melting pig iron in a reverberatory furnace (e.g. to produce wrought iron) </mm> </dd></dl>
